Input: [3, 30, 34, 5, 9]
Convert to strings â†’ ["3", "30", "34", "5", "9"]

Step 1: Start Sorting Comparisons
We will apply myCompare() to compare all possible pairs using:

java
Copy
Edit
(s1 + s2).compareTo(s2 + s1)
â¡ï¸ Compare "30" and "3"
"303" vs "330"

"303".compareTo("330") = Negative â†’ s1 comes before s2

No Swap

â¡ï¸ Compare "34" and "30"
"3430" vs "3034"

"3430".compareTo("3034") = Positive â†’ s1 comes before s2

Swap "34" and "30"

âœ… Array After Comparison: ["3", "34", "30", "5", "9"]

â¡ï¸ Compare "5" and "34"
"534" vs "345"

"534".compareTo("345") = Positive â†’ s1 comes before s2

Swap "5" and "34"

âœ… Array After Comparison: ["3", "5", "34", "30", "9"]

â¡ï¸ Compare "9" and "5"
"95" vs "59"

"95".compareTo("59") = Positive â†’ s1 comes before s2

Swap "9" and "5"

âœ… Array After Comparison: ["3", "9", "5", "34", "30"]

Step 2: Continue Sorting
Now the comparisons continue to finalize the correct order.

â¡ï¸ Compare "9" and "3"
"93" vs "39"

"93".compareTo("39") = Positive â†’ s1 comes before s2

Swap "9" and "3"

âœ… Array After Comparison: ["9", "3", "5", "34", "30"]

â¡ï¸ Compare "5" and "3"
"53" vs "35"

"53".compareTo("35") = Positive â†’ s1 comes before s2

Swap "5" and "3"

âœ… Final Sorted Array:

